Ch.9 Multicollinearity

Multicollinearity Diagnostics

  • We will use the â€˜Acetylene Dataâ€™ (Example 9.1, p.299). This dataset concerns the percentage of conversion of \(n\)-heptance (P) to acetylene and three explantory variables (Temp, H2, Cont).

  • We wish to fit a full quadratic model, \[ P = \gamma_0 + \gamma_1 T + \gamma_2 H + \gamma_3 C + \gamma_{12} TH + \gamma_{13} TC + \gamma_{23} HC + \gamma_{11} T^2 + \gamma_{22} H^2 + \gamma_{33} C^2 + \epsilon, \] where \(T\), \(H\), \(C\) are scaled variables of Temp, H2, and Cont, respectively.

  • Use the scale() function to subtract average and divide by the standard deviation.

acetylene <- read.csv("acetylene.csv")
colnames(acetylene) <- c("Obs", "P", "Temp", "H2", "Cont") 
lmfit <- lm(P ~ poly(scale(Temp), scale(H2), scale(Cont), degree = 2, raw = TRUE), 
            data = acetylene)
summary(lmfit)

LS fit

  • The least-squares fit is \[ \hat{P} = 35.896 + 4.004 T + 2.778 H -8.042 C -6.457 TH -26.98 TC -3.768 HC -12.524 T^2 -0.973 H^2 -11.593 C^2. \]

  • Fix H2 to 12.44 (average of H2) and draw the regression surface. Mark the observed values by black points. It can be seen from the figure below, that the model fits the data well, but extrapolation performance is poor. For example, some predicted values of P are negative (it should be in [0,100], since this value represents a percentage). A likely cause of this is the strong correlation between Cont and Temp, which makes the least-squares estimates of the regression coefficients very poor.

Examination of the Correlation Matrix

  • If regressors \(x_i\) and \(x_j\) are nearly linearly dependent, then \(|r_{ij}|\) (\(r_{ij}\): correlation between \(x_i\) and \(x_j\)) will be near 1.

  • Suppose that \(x_i\)s are scaled as \[ x_i^* = \frac{x_i - \bar{x}_i}{s_{x_i}} \frac{1}{\sqrt{n-1}}, \] where \(s_{x_i}\) is the standard deviation of \(x_i\). With \(\mathbf{X} = [x_1^*, \dots, x_k^*]\), \(\mathbf{X}^\top\mathbf{X} = (r_{ij})_{ij}\).

  • However, this is helpful in detecting near-linear dependence between pairs of regressors only.

X <- model.matrix(lmfit)
XPX <- cor(X[,-1])

Variance Inflation Factors (VIFs)

  • To compute VIF, use the vif() function from the R package rms.

  • The textbook suggests using vif() from the package car. However, this function does not work properly for lm objects obtained from the poly() function.

  • The maximum VIF of the Acetylene dataset is 6563.35, which means that multicollinearity problem exists. Also, linear terms involving T and C have large VIFs, indicating they are involved in the multicollinearity.

# install.packages("rms")
library(rms)
vif(lmfit)

  • Using the relationship that \(\operatorname{VIF}_j = C_{jj}\), where \(\mathbf{C} = (C_{ij})_{ij}\) is the inverse of the correlation matrix, the following code derives the equivalent result. Refer to lecture note Ch.9, p.2.
XPX |> solve() |> diag()

Eigensystem Analysis

  • Inspect the condition number of the correlation matrix of regressors. The function kappa() computes the condition number of a matrix. When exact = FALSE, it approximates the computation.

  • Following result indicates a problem with multicollinearity for the Acetylene dataset.

kappa(XPX, exact = TRUE)
## [1] 43381.31
  • Condition number is defined as \(\kappa = \lambda_\text{max}/\lambda_\text{min}\), where \(\lambda\) denotes the eigenvalue of the correlation matrix.
e <- eigen(XPX)$values # eigenvalues
max(e) / min(e)
## [1] 43381.31

Ridge Regression

  • Ridge regression can be used when there is a problem with the multicollinearity. The ridge estimator \(\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}_R\) is defined as the minimizer of \[ (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta})^\top(\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta}) + k \boldsymbol{\beta}^\top\boldsymbol{\beta}, \] where \(k\geq 0\) is a constant. It can be shown that the solution to the problem above is \[ \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}_R = (\mathbf{X}^\top\mathbf{X} + k\mathbf{I})^{-1}\mathbf{X}^\top\boldsymbol{y}. \]

  • The R package glmnet provides a function for fitting the ridge regression model. (And much more models that are not the topic of this course.)

CAUTION 1: In glmnet(), alpha should be set to 0 to conduct the ridge regression.

CAUTION 2: The lambda argument is a little bit different from the \(k\) used above. It is a regularization argument as \(k\), but due to different objective function used in the glmnet(), \(k\) and lambdaâ€™s scales are different.

# install.packages("glmnet")
library(glmnet)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## Loaded glmnet 4.1-8
X <- model.matrix(lmfit)[,-1]
y <- acetylene$P
lmfit.ridge <- glmnet(x = X, y = y, alpha = 0) # `lambda`s are automatically chosen
lmfit.ridge |> coef()

Ch.10 Variable Selection and Model Building

  • In most practical problems, the analyst has a large pool of possible candidate regressors, of which only a few are likely to be important. Finding an appropriate subset of regressors for the model is called the variable selection problem.

Criteria for Evaluating Subset Regression Models

  • We will use the â€˜Hald Cement Dataâ€™ (Table B.21, p.593). This dataset contains 13 observations with five variables (y, x1, x2, x3, x4).
hald <- read.csv("hald.csv")
lmfit <- lm(y ~ ., data = hald) # y ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4
  • Suppose that the model includes \(p\) terms, i.e., \(p-1\) regressors and an intercept.
Criterion Formula R function
Coefficient of multiple determination (\(R_p^2\)) \(R_p^2 = \frac{SS_R(p)}{SS_T}\) summary(lmfit)$r.squared
Adjusted \(R^2\) (\(R^2_{Adj,p}\)) \(R_{Adj,p}^2 = 1 - \frac{n-1}{n-p}(1-R^2_p)\) summary(lmfit)$adj.r.squared
Residual mean square (\(MS_E(p)\)) \(MS_E(p) = \frac{SS_E(p)}{n-p}\) summary(lmfit)$sigma^2
Mallowâ€™s \(C_p\) \(C_p = \frac{SS_E(p)}{\hat\sigma^2} - n + 2p\) -
Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) \(AIC = -2\log(L) + 2p\) AIC(lmfit)
Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC) \(BIC = -2\log(L) + p\log(n)\) BIC(lmfit)

CAUTION: Output of AIC() and BIC() differs from the formula given above by an additive constant independent of \(p\).

summary(lmfit)$r.squared # R^2
## [1] 0.9823756
summary(lmfit)$adj.r.squared # R^2_Adj
## [1] 0.9735634
summary(lmfit)$sigma^2 # MSE
## [1] 5.982955
AIC(lmfit) # AIC
## [1] 65.83669
BIC(lmfit) # BIC
## [1] 69.22639

Variable Selection

All possible regressions

  • Use the regsubsets() function in the leaps package. Set the argument method to "exhaustive" to conduct â€˜all possible regressionsâ€™.
  • Note that when \(p\) is fixed, all criteria above are equivalent. That is, whether you use AIC, BIC, SSE, \(R^2\)â€¦ does not affect the choice of the â€˜best subset of regressorsâ€™ when \(p\) is fixed.
# install.packages("leaps")
library(leaps)
reg <- regsubsets(y ~ ., data = hald, method = "exhaustive")
reg.summary <- summary(reg)
data.frame(reg.summary$outmat,
           R2 = reg.summary$rsq,
           R2Adj = reg.summary$adjr2,
           SSE = reg.summary$rss,
           Cp = reg.summary$cp,
           BIC = reg.summary$bic)
##          x1 x2 x3 x4        R2     R2Adj       SSE         Cp        BIC
## 1  ( 1 )           * 0.6745420 0.6449549 883.86692 138.730833  -9.462884
## 2  ( 1 )  *  *       0.9786784 0.9744140  57.90448   2.678242 -42.329587
## 3  ( 1 )  *  *     * 0.9823355 0.9764473  47.97273   3.018233 -42.210745
## 4  ( 1 )  *  *  *  * 0.9823756 0.9735634  47.86364   5.000000 -39.675391

  • Among the \(2^4\) possible regression equations, the output above shows the best subset for each \(k=1, 2, 3, 4\).

  • When using \(R^2_{Adj}\) for criterion, the regression model with x1, x2, and x4 is the â€˜bestâ€™. (Intercept term is always included.)

coef(reg, 3) # estimated regression coefficients when k=3
## (Intercept)          x1          x2          x4 
##  71.6483070   1.4519380   0.4161098  -0.2365402
  • When using \(R^2\) for criterion, we see that after the two regressors (x1 and x2) are in the model, there is little to be gained in terms of \(R^2\) by introducing additional variables.
# ?plot.regsubsets

plot(reg, scale="Cp")

Stepwise regression models

  • Evaluating all possible regressions can be computationally burdensome. Hence, when there are many regressor candidates, one may prefer stepwise-type procedures: (1) forward selection, (2) backward elimination, and (3) stepwise regression. We only consider (1) and (2) in this lab session.

  • Forward selection:

reg <- regsubsets(y ~ ., data = hald, method = "forward")
reg.summary <- summary(reg)
data.frame(reg.summary$outmat,
           R2 = reg.summary$rsq,
           R2Adj = reg.summary$adjr2,
           SSE = reg.summary$rss,
           Cp = reg.summary$cp,
           BIC = reg.summary$bic)

Ch.12 Introduction to Nonlinear Regression

  • We consider the â€˜Puromycin Dataâ€™ (Example 12.4, p.414). The Michaelisâ€“Menten model is used to relate the initial velocity of an enzymatic reaction \(y\) to the substrate concentration \(x\). The model is \[ y = \frac{\theta_1 x}{x + \theta_2} + \epsilon. \]
library(readxl)
Puromycin = read_xls("Puromycin.xls")
plot(y ~ x, data = Puromycin)

  • The model above can be linearlized as \[ y^\prime = \beta_0 + \beta_1 u + \epsilon \] where \(y^\prime = 1/y\), \(u = 1/x\), \(\beta_0 = 1/\theta_1\), and \(\beta_1 = \theta_2/\theta_1\) (see the lecture note).

  • Observe that the constant-variance assumption is unreasonable for the transformed model. Also, model does not fit the data well at high values of \(x\). This explains the need for a nonlinear regression.

lmfit <- lm(1/y ~ I(1/x), data = Puromycin)
par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(1/y ~ I(1/x), data = Puromycin)
abline(lmfit)
plot(y ~ x, data = Puromycin)
lines(Puromycin$x, 1/fitted.values(lmfit))

  • We will use the nls() (nonlinear least squares) function. It uses a Gaussâ€“Newton algorithm. You can use summary(), coef() (coefficients()), fitted.values(), and residuals() functions as if using the lm() function.
lmfit <- nls(y ~ I(t1*x/(t2+x)), data = Puromycin, 
             start = list(t1=205, t2=0.08))
summary(lmfit)
## 
## Formula: y ~ I(t1 * x/(t2 + x))
## 
## Parameters:
##     Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## t1 2.127e+02  6.947e+00  30.615 3.24e-11 ***
## t2 6.412e-02  8.281e-03   7.743 1.57e-05 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 10.93 on 10 degrees of freedom
## 
## Number of iterations to convergence: 5 
## Achieved convergence tolerance: 4.15e-06
plot(y ~ x, data = Puromycin)
lines(Puromycin$x, fitted.values(lmfit))

  • Observe that the overall fit is satisfactory.

Ch.13 Generalized Linear Models (GLMs)

  • We consider the â€˜Penumoconiosis Dataâ€™ (Example 13.1, p.445). This data concerns the proportion of coal miners who exhibit symptoms of severe pneumoconiosis (\(y\)) and the number of years of exposure (\(x\)).

  • The glm() function can be used to fit many types of generalized linear models, such as logistic regression, poisson regression, etc. The syntax of the glm() function is similar to that of lm(), except that we must pass in the argument family = binomial in order to tell R to run a logistic regression rather than some other type of generalized linear model.

  • A response is given as a two-column integer matrix: the first column gives the number of successes and the second the number of failures.

pneumoconiosis <- read.csv("pneumoconiosis.csv")
colnames(pneumoconiosis) <- c("x","pneum","miners","y")
glmfit <- glm(cbind(pneum, miners-pneum) ~ x, family = binomial, data = pneumoconiosis)
summary(glmfit)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = cbind(pneum, miners - pneum) ~ x, family = binomial, 
##     data = pneumoconiosis)
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept) -4.79648    0.56859  -8.436  < 2e-16 ***
## x            0.09346    0.01543   6.059 1.37e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 56.9028  on 7  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance:  6.0508  on 6  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 32.877
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4

  • Why canâ€™t we just write y ~ x? Recall that in the logistic regression model, \(y_i\) takes on the value either 0 or 1. It is \(E(y_i)\) that is between 0 and 1. In the dataset above, y takes a value between 0 and 1. This means that pneumoconiosis$y is not in an appropriate form for the logisitic regression model. In fact, it is in a summarized form.

  • For example, y[8] == 5/11 means that the raw data is actually 11 observations with 5 ones (success) and 6 zeros (failure). This is exactly what the code above supplies to the glm() function: the number of successes and failures. However, if you just write y ~ x, information on the total number of cases (miners) is lost.

  • So if you convert the dataset to its raw form, you do not have to specify the response in a matrix form.

success <- sum(pneumoconiosis$pneum)
failure <- sum(pneumoconiosis$miners) - success
y.new <- rep(c(1,0),c(success, failure))
x.new <- c(rep(pneumoconiosis$x, pneumoconiosis$pneum),
           rep(pneumoconiosis$x, pneumoconiosis$miners - pneumoconiosis$pneum))
glm(y.new ~ x.new, family = binomial, data = pneumoconiosis)
## 
## Call:  glm(formula = y.new ~ x.new, family = binomial, data = pneumoconiosis)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)        x.new  
##    -4.79648      0.09346  
## 
## Degrees of Freedom: 370 Total (i.e. Null);  369 Residual
## Null Deviance:       270.2 
## Residual Deviance: 219.3     AIC: 223.3
  • Otherwise, you can give the total number cases using the argument weights.
glm(y ~ x, family = binomial, weights = miners, data = pneumoconiosis)
## Warning in eval(family$initialize): non-integer #successes in a binomial glm!
## 
## Call:  glm(formula = y ~ x, family = binomial, data = pneumoconiosis, 
##     weights = miners)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)            x  
##    -4.79613      0.09345  
## 
## Degrees of Freedom: 7 Total (i.e. Null);  6 Residual
## Null Deviance:       56.9 
## Residual Deviance: 6.056     AIC: 32.88
  • You can use summary(), coef() (coefficients()), fitted.values(), and residuals() functions as if using the lm() function.
coef(glmfit)
fitted.values(glmfit)
residuals(glmfit)
  • The predict() function can be used to make predictions. When the argument type = "response" \(\exp(\boldsymbol{x}^\top\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}})/[1+\exp(\boldsymbol{x}^\top\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}})]\) is returned. If this argument is omitted, the default option is used (type = "link"), and the function returns \(\boldsymbol{x}^\top\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}\). To make predictions at new \(\boldsymbol{x}\), use the newdata argument. If no newdata is supplied, then the predict() function returns the predictions for the data that was used to fit the logistic regression model.
predict(glmfit)
